<tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>7736</anchor> <rss>jms-002Y.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Warning</taxon> <addr>jms-002Y</addr>  <route>jms-002Y.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>2</month> <day>21</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Way-below vs. positivity</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>At first glance, the definitions of the <link href="jms-002V.xml" type="local" title="Way-below relation">way-below relation</link> and <link href="jms-001M.xml" type="local" title="Positivity">positivity</link> appear very similar:</p><tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="true" root="false"><frontmatter><trail><crumb>1</crumb></trail> <anchor>7737</anchor> <rss>jms-002V.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>jms-002V</addr>  <route>jms-002V.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>2</month> <day>21</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>The way-below relation</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Let <tex>x,y:D</tex> be two elements of a dcpo <tex>D</tex>; we say that <tex>x</tex> is <em>way below</em> <tex>y</tex>, written <tex>x \ll  y</tex>, when for any directed subset <tex>I \subseteq  D</tex> such that <tex>y \sqsubseteq   \bigsqcup{I}</tex>, there exists <tex>z \in  I</tex> such that <tex>x \sqsubseteq  z</tex>.</p><p>(Adapted from <link href="dejong-2023-thesis.xml" type="local" title="Tom de Jong’s thesis">Tom de Jong’s thesis</link>.)</p></mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="true" root="false"><frontmatter><trail><crumb>2</crumb></trail> <anchor>7738</anchor> <rss>jms-001M.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>jms-001M</addr>  <route>jms-001M.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>2</month> <day>14</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>The positive elements of a pointed dcpo</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>An element <tex>u</tex> of a <link href="jms-001S.xml" type="local" title="Pointed">pointed</link> dpco <tex>A</tex> is called <em>positive</em> when for any semidirected subset <tex>I \subseteq  A</tex>, if <tex>u \sqsubseteq   \bigsqcup{I}</tex> then <tex>I</tex> is inhabited. We will write <tex>\mathsf{pos} \,{u}</tex> to mean that <tex>u</tex> is a positive element.</p><p>(This is adapted from <link href="johnstone-1984.xml" type="local" title="Johnstone">Johnstone</link>’s definition of positive elements of frames to the case of dcpos by <link href="dejong-2023-thesis.xml" type="local" title="Tom de Jong">Tom de Jong</link>.)</p></mainmatter> </tree><p>One is tempted to assert “an element <tex>a:A</tex> of a <link href="jms-001S.xml" type="local" title="Pointed">pointed</link> dcpo <tex>A</tex> is <link href="jms-001M.xml" type="local" title="Positive">positive</link> if and only if <tex>\bot \ll  a</tex>”, but note that positivity involves a semidirected subset whereas <link href="jms-002V.xml" type="local" title="Way-below">way-below</link> involves a <em>directed</em> subset. Indeed, we always have <tex>\bot \ll  a</tex>.</p></mainmatter> <backmatter><contributions/> <context/> <related><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>7739</anchor> <rss>jms-002V.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>jms-002V</addr>  <route>jms-002V.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>2</month> <day>21</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>The way-below relation</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Let <tex>x,y:D</tex> be two elements of a dcpo <tex>D</tex>; we say that <tex>x</tex> is <em>way below</em> <tex>y</tex>, written <tex>x \ll  y</tex>, when for any directed subset <tex>I \subseteq  D</tex> such that <tex>y \sqsubseteq   \bigsqcup{I}</tex>, there exists <tex>z \in  I</tex> such that <tex>x \sqsubseteq  z</tex>.</p><p>(Adapted from <link href="dejong-2023-thesis.xml" type="local" title="Tom de Jong’s thesis">Tom de Jong’s thesis</link>.)</p></mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>7740</anchor> <rss>jms-001S.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>jms-001S</addr>  <route>jms-001S.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>2</month> <day>14</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Pointed dcpo</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>A dcpo is called <em>pointed</em> when it has a bottom element <tex>\bot</tex> under the information order.</p></mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>7741</anchor> <rss>jms-001M.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>jms-001M</addr>  <route>jms-001M.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>2</month> <day>14</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>The positive elements of a pointed dcpo</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>An element <tex>u</tex> of a <link href="jms-001S.xml" type="local" title="Pointed">pointed</link> dpco <tex>A</tex> is called <em>positive</em> when for any semidirected subset <tex>I \subseteq  A</tex>, if <tex>u \sqsubseteq   \bigsqcup{I}</tex> then <tex>I</tex> is inhabited. We will write <tex>\mathsf{pos} \,{u}</tex> to mean that <tex>u</tex> is a positive element.</p><p>(This is adapted from <link href="johnstone-1984.xml" type="local" title="Johnstone">Johnstone</link>’s definition of positive elements of frames to the case of dcpos by <link href="dejong-2023-thesis.xml" type="local" title="Tom de Jong">Tom de Jong</link>.)</p></mainmatter> </tree></related> <backlinks/> <references/></backmatter></tree>